1. Introduction to the project

This project will be taking a given data set, interpreting it as a time series and then performing some calculations and interpretations on it using prophet, as well as other R functions. I will now introduce the selected data.

1.1 What is the USUnemployment data set?

The data set shows the number of unemployed individuals (in 000s) from 1948 and 1981 in the US on a monthly basis. The data, as we will see later, has been split into 4 groups:

  • Female teenager (age 16-19)
  • Male teenager (age 16-19)
  • Female adult (age 20+)
  • Male adult (age 20+)

The data comes from a statistical study from Andrews D.F. and Herzberg H. M.

I selected this data set for two key reasons:

  • I have previously read academic papers by Herzberg during A Levels and I wanted to further investigate his work

  • My interest in the social side to economics, namely how unemployment changes over time, and if it can be quantitatively forecasted, or whether additional cofactors and considerations need to be taken into consideration (e.g. political and economic unsystematic risk)

1.2 Objectives of this project

Unemployment is often a word thrown around loosely in modern day economics and politics, so I decided it would be a useful endeavor to study some 30 years in the USA’s most relevant century, where they grew rapidly to be a world superpower. The data set aids me in one respect, as it is not affected (albeit significantly) by WW1 and WW2, and likewise the later conflicts of the 20th century.

Investigating and understanding this data, I would like to:

  • Investigate trends, seasonality and their relative size
    • Use linear regression to gain a better understanding of these trends
    • Use graphs to better investigate my linear regressions
  • Investigate data points of interests -Understand why these points exist (e.g. economic policy, global events etc.)
  • Understand the general pattern, growth/decay and development of unemployment figures
  • Consider these results for different time frames
    • To see if there are any patterns of acceleration or deceleration
    • To investigates periods of plateaus or humps in the unemployment rate
  • Generate predictions using my data and arrive at a general conclusion of my findings

4. Identifying pattern with the Spencer Filter

As gathered earlier, the pattern is increasing over time. I could use the Spencer filter to predict future values, but I will use the prophet tool and other more advanced tools to do that. For now, I will just use the Spencer Filter to better understand the existing pattern.

library(signal)
## Warning: package 'signal' was built under R version 4.3.3
## 
## Attaching package: 'signal'
## The following object is masked from 'package:Rssa':
## 
##     roots
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, poly
plot(USUnemployment)
lines(stats :: filter(USUnemployment,spencerFilter()),type="l",col="red")
legend("topleft",legend=c("Data","Spencer Filter"),col=c("black","red"),lty=1)

  • The 1955-58 decrease can be explained by:
    • Post war recovery, which was a period of rapid growth following the end of WW2 that stretched into the 1950s
    • Sustained GDP growth in the 1950s, often labelled as the “Eisenhower Boom”, after the US President Dwight Eisenhower who served from 1953 to 1961 -Increased government spending -Technological advancements -Post war saw an increase in the labour force participation rate (% of the population that is either employed or seeking employment)
  • The decrease in the 1960s can be explained by:
    • Increased consumer spending
    • Low point of unemployment in 1968
    • Social activism such as the Civil Rights Movement and others allowed more women and African Americans to join the workforce
    • Lyndon Johnson (US President at the time) had his “Great Society” program
      • War on Poverty incentive
      • Creation of Medicare and Medicaid
  • In the increase in the 1970s is likely due to :
    • Oil price shocks
    • Increased global competition e.g. USSR
    • Tighter monetary policy by the Federal reserve
    • More restrictive fiscal policy to curb inflation
  • The decrease in the 1980s were likely due to:
    • Implementation of “Reaganomics”, the economic strategy of then US President Ronald Reagan
      • Tax cuts
      • Deregulation
      • Budget deficits by funding the military heavily

We can see that even though these external factors to tend to decrease unemployment, it is constantly on a rise over the time period, with typically more peaks than troughs. This is definitely due to the population increasing rapidly over this time span.

6. Inspecting the nature of residuals

6.1 Box Cox and Breusch–Pagan

Using the Box Cox test we can interpret whether the noise is homo or heteroskedastic

BoxCox.lambda(USUnemployment) -> lambda
USUnemploymentBC = BoxCox(USUnemployment,lambda)
plot(USUnemploymentBC)

Here, we can observe that the plot is not symmetric, so we clearly have unemployment increasing over time. This has now been established.

We can also use the Breusch–Pagan Test for Heteroskedasticity, which is based on the hypothesis:

  • H0 the time series is homoskedastic
  • H1 the time series is heteroskedastic
lmtest::bptest(USUnemployment~time)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  USUnemployment ~ time
## BP = 19.269, df = 1, p-value = 1.135e-05
lmtest::bptest(USUnemploymentBC~time(USUnemploymentBC))
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  USUnemploymentBC ~ time(USUnemploymentBC)
## BP = 3.3682, df = 1, p-value = 0.06647
lmtest::bptest(logUSUnemp~time(logUSUnemp))
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  logUSUnemp ~ time(logUSUnemp)
## BP = 15.559, df = 1, p-value = 7.996e-05

Given the small p values of USUnemployment and logUSUnemp, it is clear that we cannot reject the null hypothesis and therefore the time series and the logarithmic series are not homoskedastic. But the Box Cox interpretation could be due to its higher p value.

Therefore, it is reasonable to conclude that as much as unemployment has grown across the some 33 year period, it is also relevant that is remains relatively similar across the period, hence the earlier prediction does not seem very reasonable.

6.2 Brockwell-Davies decomposition

res = stats::decompose(USUnemployment)$random
plot(res)

We need to clean these residuals by taking out NA values, so we only care about when the data starts and ends (July 1948 and June 1981 respectively)

res = window(res,start=c(1948,7),end = c(1981,6))

We can now plot correlograms to show the containment of residuals across the time series

acf(res,type="covariance")

acf(res)

As lag increases, the autocorrelation falls rapidly, with the magnitude being highest in lower levels of lag. It should be noted that the autocorrelation values fluctuate in both directions, eluding to the fact that unemployment oscillates in small periods. The significance levels indicate that there are only extreme values in early stages, which may be more random chance (i.e. external factors)

6.3 Testing stationarity

We can use augmented Dickey Fuller test and Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin test to asses stationary of the time series

Note: ADF: H0 = series is not stationary and # KPSS: H0 = stationary

We will also need the feasts package to perform these

tseries::adf.test(res) 
## Warning in tseries::adf.test(res): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  res
## Dickey-Fuller = -8.5742, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
feasts::unitroot_kpss(res)
##   kpss_stat kpss_pvalue 
## 0.009630468 0.100000000

Both suggest that the series is stationary, but is it white noise?

We can say no based on the correlogram, but we can test it formally. Let H0: white noise, no correlations

Box.test(res, type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 137.78, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

Due to the low p value, we conclude this is not white noise.

7. Introducing Prophet

7.1 Establishing progress before Prophet

What have we found so far?

  • Unemployment is not random and does adhere to a pattern, this is prevalent in many periods such as the mid 1970s and 1950s, where there are rises and dips respectively
  • The average unemployed is likely skewed due to increases in latter years
  • Transforming the data reveals no additional information, so there is no point using quadratic, cubic or logarithmic data
  • Seasonality has little effect
  • Residuals suggest mostly stationary and heteroskadistic data, however there is some hints of homoskedacity in the form of the Box Cox test, likely due to unemployment not necessarily exceeding a relative boundary of 2 million to 9 million
  • This data does not adhere to White Noise
  • Predictions so far are futile due to the oscillating nature, and the exposure to real world events and other factors such as legislation which cannot be implemented into this time series

7.2 Why do we use Prophet?

Addressing the initial objectives, I would like to look into years with greater focus and also develop more realistic predictions. I will be using Prophet to do this.

Note: Ensure that the Prophet package is installed

library(prophet)
## Warning: package 'prophet' was built under R version 4.3.3

To effectively use prophet, I am going to specify my time series.

USUn.df = data.frame(
  ds=zoo::as.yearmon(time(USUnemployment)), 
  y=USUnemployment)

I can use the prophet function, specifying seasonality to create a more accurate understanding of the initial data.

prophet_model = prophet(USUn.df,weekly.seasonality = TRUE,daily.seasonality = TRUE)

I can then take this improved data and predict 3 years into the future

forecast = prophet::make_future_dataframe(prophet_model, periods=36, freq="month")
prediction = predict(prophet_model, forecast)
plot(prophet_model,prediction)

Here, we can see a similar pattern to the earlier prediction, with a general increase with small oscillations. However, as we cannot supply external events and subsequent shifts to unemployment, this is not particularly reflective of the real world unemployment figures.

So we can use this prediction as a rough guidelines. We can assume that based on this three year prediction, it is not worthwhile computing a 40 year prediction to modern times.

However, an added bonus to the plot is the shaded area around the line, allowing for a confidence interval to be investigated.

To investigate key components, such as trend and impact of the day of the week, date and hour of the day, I can do the following plot:

prophet_plot_components(prophet_model, prediction)

I can conclude:

  • Unemployment trend increases over time
  • The day with the most unemployed people is Tuesday, and the least is Friday
  • In the year, the number of unemployed is highest at the end of February/ start of March
  • Most people are made unemployed between 10pm and 2am. I suspect this to be because most data points are recorded at midnight of a new day, and this does not suggest much to overall data
    • I would expect the true value to between 9am and 5pm, to reflect most working hours, where people are made unemployed

Now, I want to be able to investigate particular areas in finer detail graphically. I can do this with the following plot:

dyplot.prophet(prophet_model, prediction)

8. Concluding my findings

Addressing the original objectives, we can conclude that:

  • Trends indicate a general increase in unemployment over the years
    • From linear regression models we understand that roughly 60-70% of this is general increases, with the remaining 20-30% being up to external factors
    • Variance is not constant; suggesting a lack of homoskedacity
    • There is no white noise present
  • Key points of rising or falling interest rates can be explained by external factors, such as economic policy, fiscal policy, presidential policy etc.
  • It is difficult to conclusively predict the data, due to the exposure to external shocks that the unemployment levels often experience
  • Using the interactive plot, we can focus on these key areas to highlight when shocks occur
  • We have developed an understanding that some days of the week have generally higher levels of unemployment e.g. Tuesday is greater than Friday

Therefore, we can conclude that unemployment did increase over the 33 year period of 1948-1981, particularly due to population increasing rapidly. It should be considered that the external environment (e.g. politics and economics) has a large impact on this process. Moving forward, were I to be asked to effectively predict the next 10 years or so (i.e. from now to 2034), I would require more information. This would include information from 1981 to modern day, regarding global events, US economic policy etc. Moving to predictions, I would try to include additional non-linear factors such as random presidential changes and possibly changes in technology, such as the rapid development of AI; this will certainly affect the unemployment rate in jobs which can be automated.
